{"id":"mai-t1i8","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 3: CRDT Sync Root Cause — Stale Merge Base Snowball","tags":["research","oracle"],"body":"# Oracle 3: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian — Full Investigationnn## 1. Instructor Framing Assessmentnn**Framing bias check:** The instructor's framing is MOSTLY ACCURATE but has one subtle bias — it implies the CRDT itself might be wrong or unnecessary. After reading all primary sources, I find the CRDT is the right tool, but it's being MISUSED. The framing correctly identifies the symptoms and the lastSyncBody TODO, but underestimates how fundamentally broken the merge base selection is.nn**Verified claims:**n- ✅ mergeViaCRDT uses creationBody as the 3-way merge basen- ✅ lastSyncBody() returns empty string (dead code path)n- ✅ Document gets garbled with 40x line fragment duplicationn- ✅ Obsidian saves frequently (every ~2 seconds of inactivity, full file write)nn**One claim to refine:** The instructor says \"The lastSyncBody() function has a TODO and returns empty string.\" This is true, but lastSyncBody() is NEVER CALLED. The merge function uses creationBody parameter instead. The function is dead code but the intent was right — tracking the last-sync base is the correct solution.nn## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)nn### Root Cause: Stale Base Snowball EffectnnThe bug is a **snowball duplication** caused by using the wrong merge base on repeated syncs. Here's the exact mechanism:nn**Cycle 1:**n1. Note created with body A (creationBody = A)n2. File materialized with content An3. User edits file to content B in Obsidiann4. Daemon triggers SyncDocsn5. mergeViaCRDT called: state.Body=A, fileContent=B, creationBody=An6. base=A, notePeer: diff(A→A)=noop, filePeer: diff(A→B)=editsn7. Merge produces B ✅ CORRECTnn**Cycle 2:**n1. Note now has body=B, YDocState has Bn2. User edits file from B to C in Obsidiann3. Daemon triggers SyncDocsn4. mergeViaCRDT called: state.Body=B, fileContent=C, creationBody=A (still the original!)n5. base=A (!), notePeer: diff(A→B)=edits, filePeer: diff(A→C)=editsn6. Both peers started from A, applied independent edits. CRDT merges BOTH sets of changesn7. Since B and C share content from A, the shared content stays. But changes from A→B and A→C include overlapping insertions at similar positionsn8. CRDT inserts both sets — producing DUPLICATIONnn**Cycle 3+:** The problem compounds. Each sync, the creationBody (A) diverges further from current content. The diff(A→currentNote) produces massive insert ops. The diff(A→currentFile) produces similar massive insert ops. Both get inserted, producing exponential duplication.nn### Why This Exactly Matches the Symptomsnn- \"line fragments get duplicated 40+ times\" — After N sync cycles, content that was inserted in cycle 1 gets re-inserted in cycles 2, 3, ... N because each cycle re-diffs against the original creation bodyn- \"2700 words → 15,778 characters of duplicated fragments\" — Classic snowball: each merge adds more duplicated content, which makes the NEXT merge even worsen- Fragment-level duplication (not line-level) — The diff algorithm (Myers diff via go-diff) operates at character level, so partial lines get duplicatednn## 3. Research Pathnn### Path A: CRDT mechanics (PRIMARY)n- Read pkg/crdt/crdt.go — standard y-crdt wrapper, no bugs foundn- Read pkg/crdt/diff.go — uses sergi/go-diff Myers diff, correct implementationn- Read yrs-wasi/src/lib.rs — standard yrs wrapper, unique client IDs, correctn- Read crdt_test.go — concurrent merge tests pass, CRDT works correctlyn- Read diff_test.go — diff + apply round-trips correctlyn- **Finding:** The CRDT layer is correct. It merges exactly as designed. The problem is what we FEED it.nn### Path B: mergeViaCRDT logic (PRIMARY, ROOT CAUSE FOUND)n- Read pkg/notes/docs.go line 520-600n- The merge creates a BASE doc, then two peers from that basen- Base comes from creationBody parameter, which comes from engine.Get(id) — the CREATION noten- This base NEVER changes after the note is createdn- Each sync: notePeer applies diff(creation→current note), filePeer applies diff(creation→current file)n- When note and file have BOTH diverged from creation, BOTH diffs contain large overlapping insertionsn- CRDT faithfully preserves ALL insertions from ALL peers → duplicationnn### Path C: Daemon behavior (SUPPORTING)n- Read cmd/mai/daemon.gon- Uses fsnotify with 500ms debounce for writes, 500ms for deletesn- On file change: calls syncFile → notes.SyncDocs(engine, w.path, w.cfg.Docs)n- Engine is CACHED per repo — same engine instance across eventsn- **Key finding:** Cached engine means YDocState accumulates across syncs, but the creationBody stays fixed. This makes the snowball worse because the YDoc grows with each bad merge.nn### Path D: Obsidian save behavior (SUPPORTING)n- Obsidian auto-saves every ~2 seconds of inactivityn- Obsidian writes the FULL file content each time (not a diff/patch)n- Obsidian uses Node.js fs.writeFile (Electron), which on macOS does a direct write (NOT atomic rename)n- On some platforms, there may be a brief remove+create cycle, but daemon already handles this with delete debouncingn- **Key finding:** Full-file writes are NOT the problem. The problem is that the merge function doesn't track what content was last synced.nn### Path E: How other tools handle thisn- **obsidian-git plugin**: Uses plain git merge. Conflicts produce \u003c\u003c\u003c\u003c\u003c\u003c\u003c markers. Users resolve manually. No CRDT.n- **Logseq**: Uses git for sync. Conflicts are manual. No CRDT.n- **Dendron/Foam**: Same — git-based, manual conflict resolutionn- **Obsidian Sync (official)**: Last-write-wins by default, with .conflict copies in v1.9.7+n- **y-prosemirror**: Uses precise diffs (not full-document replacement) via editor bindings that track exact changesn- **Key finding:** Nobody uses CRDT for external-editor sync. CRDTs shine when you control BOTH editing endpoints. For external editors, you need a DIFFERENT strategy.nn### Path F: Known CRDT duplication patterns (CONFIRMING)n- StackOverflow Q77833526: \"Yjs interprets [full document replacement] as deleting all existing text and inserting all new text; if two users do so concurrently, they both insert the complete new text, duplicating it.\"n- Peritext paper (Ink \u0026 Switch): Documents the exact duplication mechanism when CRDTs merge overlapping insertionsn- **Key finding:** This is a KNOWN footgun with CRDTs. The solution is to compute precise diffs, which maitake already does via diff.go — but the WRONG BASE makes even precise diffs produce overlapping insertions.nn## 4. Dead Endsnn### Dead End A: \"The CRDT implementation is buggy\"nInvestigated thoroughly. crdt.go, diff.go, and lib.rs are all correct. Tests pass. The CRDT does exactly what it should — the problem is what we feed it.nn### Dead End B: \"Obsidian's atomic saves cause the problem\"nObsidian on macOS uses direct fs.writeFile, not atomic rename. Even if it did use atomic saves, the daemon handles delete debouncing correctly. Atomic saves are NOT the cause.nn### Dead End C: \"We need a different CRDT algorithm\"nNo algorithm change fixes a wrong merge base. YATA (yrs) is correct for character-level text merge. The algorithm isn't the problem.nn### Dead End D: \"The diff algorithm produces bad ops\"ndiff.go uses Myers diff (via sergi/go-diff), which is optimal. The ops are correct for the given inputs. The inputs are wrong (wrong base), not the diff.nn## 5. Key Discoveriesnn### Discovery 1: The fix is conceptually simple — track last-sync bodynThe lastSyncBody() function already has the right idea but is unimplemented. The fix:n1. After each successful sync, store a hash (or the full body) of what was written to diskn2. On next sync, use THAT as the merge base, not the creation bodyn3. This makes each sync cycle independent: diff(lastSync→noteBody) and diff(lastSync→fileContent)nn### Discovery 2: The YDoc state is actually unnecessary for this use casenThe current code creates a YDoc, loads base state, creates two peers, applies diffs, merges. But since there are only TWO parties (note and file), and syncs happen sequentially (not concurrently), this is equivalent to a 3-way text merge. You don't need a CRDT for serial 2-party sync.nnHowever, keeping the CRDT has ONE advantage: if maitake ever supports real concurrent editing (multiple agents editing the same note while a user edits the file), the CRDT becomes essential. It's future-proofing.nn### Discovery 3: The cached engine in the daemon accumulates corruptionnEach bad merge writes a new YDocState that contains the duplicated content. The next merge loads this corrupted state. The engine cache means this corrupted state persists across file events within a single daemon session.nn### Discovery 4: creationBody can be wrong toonengine.Get(id) returns the creation note. For notes created via the CLI, this is the initial body. But if the note was imported from an existing file, the creationBody IS the file content — meaning on the first edit, base=creationBody=initialFileContent, which is correct. The bug only manifests on the SECOND and subsequent edits.nn## 6. Contradicting Evidencenn### Partial contradiction: \"The tests pass\"nTestDocs_RapidEditsAllPersist passes with 10 rapid edits. Why doesn't it show duplication?nn**Resolution:** The test does sync between each edit, but the note body is ONLY changed by the file edits (no concurrent note-side edits). So on each sync: noteBody=previousFileContent=lastSyncedContent. The merge base (creationBody) differs from noteBody, but since the file was the only editor, the diff(creationBody→noteBody) produces the same edits that were already in the file. The duplication only occurs when BOTH note and file have independently changed since creation.nn### Partial contradiction: \"TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged passes\"nThis test has both note and file change, which should trigger the bug. But looking closely, it does ONE sync. The note edit sets body to \"Note edit.\" and the file says \"File edit.\" — both total replacements of \"Original.\" Since only ONE sync happens, the snowball doesn't occur. The CRDT merges the two full replacements and the test only checks \"file should win\" (which it does because file content is more recent in the CRDT timeline).nnThe bug requires MULTIPLE sync cycles where creationBody increasingly diverges from current content.nn## 7. Synthesis — The Answernn### Design: How CRDT doc sync should worknn**Core principle:** Each sync cycle must use the LAST SYNCED content as the merge base, not the creation body.nn**Implementation — Option A: Last-Sync Body Tracking (RECOMMENDED)**nn1. Add a `lastSyncHash` field to the note's event stream (stored as a `sync` event)n2. After each successful SyncDocs merge+write, emit a sync event with the hash of the written bodyn3. In mergeViaCRDT, load the last sync event's body as the base (fall back to creationBody for first sync)n4. To store the actual last-sync body (not just hash), either:n   a. Store the full body in the sync event (simple but verbose)n   b. Store a content hash + keep the body in a deduped blob storen   c. Use the YDoc state itself — the YDoc content after the last sync IS the basenn**Refined approach using YDoc as the base:**n1. After sync, save the YDoc state (already done)n2. On next sync, load the YDoc state → its Content() is the last-synced textn3. diff(ydocContent → noteBody) = note-side changes since last syncn4. diff(ydocContent → fileContent) = file-side changes since last syncn5. Apply both diff sets to the YDoc. CRDT merges correctly because the base is correct.nnWait — this is ALMOST what the code does, but with a critical flaw. Let me trace again:nnCurrent code:n```nnoteContent, _ := noteDoc.Content()  // from loaded YDocStatenbase := creationBody               // WRONG — should be noteContent!nif base == \"\" { base = noteContent } // This fallback is RIGHTn```nnThe fix is simpler than I thought: **just always use noteContent as the base.**nnWhen creationBody is empty (first sync), the code already falls back to noteContent. But when creationBody is non-empty, it OVERRIDES noteContent as the base. Remove that override.nnActually wait — there's a subtlety. The YDocState is updated by updateYDoc when the NOTE changes. So noteContent from the YDoc reflects the NOTE's current state, not the last-synced state. If the note changed since last sync, noteContent ≠ last-synced content.nnSo we need EITHER:n1. A separate \"last sync body\" or \"last sync YDoc state\" — stored when sync completesn2. OR: make the YDocState only reflect synced content (don't update it on note-side edits separately)nn**Option B: Abolish CRDT, use 3-way text merge (SIMPLER)**nnSince syncs are sequential and there are only 2 parties:n1. Track last-synced body (as text, in a file or event)n2. On sync: compute diff3(lastSync, noteBody, fileBody) using a standard 3-way mergen3. If no conflicts: apply merged resultn4. If conflicts: file wins (or mark conflict)n5. Update last-synced body to the merged resultnnThis is simpler, removes the WASM/yrs dependency for this path, and is more predictable. A good 3-way merge library for Go: github.com/hexops/gotextdiff or similar.nn**My recommendation: Option A with the YDoc fix, but store a snapshot YDoc at sync time.**nnThe YDoc gives future-proofing for multi-agent concurrent editing. The fix is:n1. When sync completes successfully, store the merged YDoc state as the \"sync checkpoint\"n2. On next sync, load the CHECKPOINT state (not the latest note YDoc state) as the basen3. diff(checkpoint → noteBody) = note changes since last syncn4. diff(checkpoint → fileBody) = file changes since last syncn5. Apply both to the checkpoint YDoc, merge, save new checkpointnnThis requires adding one new event type: `field: \"ydoc-sync\"` (the sync checkpoint), separate from `field: \"ydoc\"` (the note's current CRDT state).nn### Testing Strategynn**Unit tests for merge logic:**n1. TestMerge_SecondEditDoesNotDuplicate — create note, sync, edit file, sync, edit file again, sync. Assert no duplication.n2. TestMerge_ConcurrentNoteAndFileEdit_TwoRounds — edit both note and file, sync, edit both again, sync. Assert no duplication, both edits preserved.n3. TestMerge_SnowballRegression — 10 rapid sync cycles with file edits. Assert final content length is reasonable (no exponential growth).n4. TestMerge_EmptyBase_FirstSync — first sync with no prior checkpoint. Should work correctly.n5. TestMerge_LargeDocument_NoDuplication — 2700-word document, 5 edit cycles. Assert word count stays stable.nn**Integration tests simulating Obsidian:**n1. TestObsidianSim_FrequentSaves — Write file 10 times in 2-second intervals (mimicking Obsidian autosave). Run sync after each. Assert no corruption.n2. TestObsidianSim_AgentAndUserConcurrent — Agent edits note body while file is being edited. Sync runs between edits. Assert both changes merge cleanly.n3. TestObsidianSim_FullFileRewrite — Replace entire file content (not incremental edit). Sync. Assert clean result.nn**Adversarial tests:**n1. TestAdversarial_100SyncCycles — 100 sync rounds with alternating note and file edits. Assert content length stays bounded.n2. TestAdversarial_IdenticalEdits — Both note and file change to identical content. Assert no duplication.n3. TestAdversarial_EmptyFile — File truncated to empty. Sync. Assert note is updated (not duplicated).n4. TestAdversarial_BinaryGrowthDetection — Property test: after N syncs, content length must be O(N) not O(2^N).nn**Regression test for specific bug:**n1. TestRegression_ObsidianGarbling — Create a ~2700 word document, simulate 3 Obsidian edits with syncs between each. Assert final content \u003c 120% of expected size. This is the exact reproduction of the reported bug.nn## 8. Confidence \u0026 Caveatsnn**Confidence: 95%** that the root cause is the stale merge base (creationBody never updating).nn**Caveats:**n- I haven't RUN the code to reproduce the bug — this analysis is from reading. A reproduction test would confirm 100%.n- The YDoc checkpoint approach adds event storage overhead. For large documents, this could be significant (each sync stores a full YDoc state binary).n- The engine cache in the daemon means a fix to mergeViaCRDT alone may not be sufficient — the cached engine's in-memory state also needs to be correct after sync.nn## 9. Divergent Possibilitiesnn### Possibility A: Just use last-write-winsnThe simplest approach. File wins on every sync. No CRDT, no merge. The note body is always overwritten with the file content.n- Pro: Zero duplication risk. Trivial to implement.n- Con: Note-side edits (from agents) are silently lost if a file edit happens between note edit and sync.n- Verdict: Too lossy for a system where AI agents edit notes.nn### Possibility B: Operational Transform instead of CRDTnOT works well for 2-party sequential sync. Lower complexity than CRDT.n- Pro: No duplication possible with correct base tracking.n- Con: Still needs base tracking (same core fix). Adds a new dependency. No advantage over fixing the CRDT base.n- Verdict: Unnecessary — fixing the base solves the CRDT version.nn### Possibility C: Content-addressed snapshots + diff3nStore content-addressed snapshots at each sync point. Use standard 3-way text merge (diff3) instead of CRDT.n- Pro: Well-understood algorithm, easy to debug, no WASM dependency.n- Con: Doesn't handle true concurrent edits (two agents + user). Less future-proof.n- Verdict: Viable alternative if CRDT complexity is deemed too high. But the CRDT is already built and working — just needs the right base.nn### Possibility D: Hybrid — CRDT for agent↔agent, diff3 for agent↔filenUse the CRDT for note-side merges (multiple agents) and simple diff3 for file↔note sync.n- Pro: Right tool for each job.n- Con: Two merge paths to maintain.n- Verdict: Over-engineered for current needs.nn## Summarynn| Aspect | Finding |n|--------|---------|n| Root cause | mergeViaCRDT uses creation body as base, never updates it |n| Why duplication | Each sync re-diffs against stale base, producing overlapping insertions |n| CRDT correctness | The CRDT layer (yrs/wasm) works correctly |n| Fix | Track last-synced content as merge base (YDoc checkpoint) |n| Best approach | Store \"ydoc-sync\" checkpoint after each sync, use as base for next sync |n| Simplest correct | Always use YDoc.Content() as base when YDocState exists (2-line fix for single-editor case) |n| Testing | Multi-cycle sync tests that detect content growth / duplication |n| CRDT necessity | Not strictly needed for 2-party sync, but provides future-proofing |n","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:08:09Z","branch":"main"}
